sec.p:
The means and variances of the different immune effectors were compared between the invasive and native Egyptian geese populations. To this end, we used an extension of commonly applied linear models. Linear models assume that the response variable y is a function of a linear combination of n predictor variables x with coefficients c0,..,cn and an error ε:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$y_{i} = c_{0} + c_{1} x_{1,i} + \cdots + c_{n} x_{n,i} + {\upvarepsilon }_{i} ,$$\end{document}yi=c0+c1x1,i+⋯+cnxn,i+εi,where ε is the so-called residual variance which captures all the variation in the response variable that is not explained by the predictors. In linear models ε is assumed to be normally and independently distributed around zero. An additional usual assumption is that the variance of this distribution is a constant \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
